WEBVTT

00:00.968 --> 00:04.027
BULL: <i>I'm Dr. Jason Bull.
I'm not a lawyer.</i>

00:04.030 --> 00:07.731
<i>I'm an expert in what's
called trial science.</i>

00:07.733 --> 00:11.268
<i>I study the jury's behavioral patterns.</i>

00:11.270 --> 00:14.038
<i>I know what they're
thinking before they do.</i>

00:15.241 --> 00:18.042
<i>Everything my team learns
gets plugged into a matrix,</i>

00:18.044 --> 00:21.545
<i>which allows us to
assemble a shadow jury</i>

00:21.547 --> 00:24.748
<i>that is scary in its
predictive efficiency.</i>

00:26.986 --> 00:29.486
<i>The verdict you get depends on me.</i>

00:29.488 --> 00:32.240
<i>And that's no bull.</i>

00:32.369 --> 00:36.478
- <font color="#D81D1D">Synced and corrected by VitoSilans</font> -
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.Addic7ed.com</font> --

00:36.629 --> 00:39.096
Don't tell me plane
crashes are bad luck.

00:39.098 --> 00:41.465
You think that Malaysia
flight just disappeared?

00:41.467 --> 00:44.969
Statistically, flying is
still the safest way to travel.

00:44.971 --> 00:46.337
It's a business, isn't it?

00:46.339 --> 00:47.838
They need to be held accountable.

00:47.840 --> 00:50.107
You have to trust the pilot, but...

00:50.109 --> 00:51.608
it's a leap of faith.

00:51.610 --> 00:53.410
You get on a plane without
a second thought.

00:53.412 --> 00:55.512
But you have no idea who's flying it.

00:55.514 --> 00:58.949
(thunder rumbling)

00:58.951 --> 01:00.818
(plane rattling)

01:00.820 --> 01:02.386
FLIGHT ATTENDANT: Ladies and gentlemen,

01:02.388 --> 01:04.700
we'll be starting our
descent into Albany

01:04.702 --> 01:05.756
- in just a few moments.
- (crying)

01:05.758 --> 01:07.816
Flight attendants will
be coming through the cabin

01:07.817 --> 01:09.526
to pick up any last-minute trash items.

01:09.528 --> 01:11.428
As a reminder, we're
entering some rough air,

01:11.430 --> 01:14.698
so please remain in your
seats with seatbelts fastened.

01:14.700 --> 01:16.333
(plane continues rattling)

01:19.372 --> 01:20.304
- Ma'am.
- (sniffles)

01:20.306 --> 01:22.239
You really need to take your seat.

01:22.241 --> 01:24.808
I'm so sorry.

01:32.685 --> 01:34.485
This needs to be up, sweetie.

01:34.487 --> 01:37.221
(rumbling grows louder,
passengers gasping)

01:38.691 --> 01:40.891
(passengers screaming)

01:42.161 --> 01:45.729
BENNY: <i>It's a simple
question, Mr. Stowman.</i>

01:45.731 --> 01:47.364
VINCE: In the world history of

01:47.366 --> 01:49.767
stupid questions, that
is the stupidest question.

01:49.769 --> 01:51.935
MARISSA: Our client just torpedoed

01:51.937 --> 01:53.237
jurors two and eight.

01:53.239 --> 01:55.506
12 thinks he's a rebel.

01:55.508 --> 01:56.774
Lifelong fan, but I...

01:56.776 --> 01:58.509
- VINCE: Wanker.
- MARISSA: There goes 12.

01:58.511 --> 02:00.711
VINCE: No further questions.

02:02.148 --> 02:04.597
This is after three
days of witness prep.

02:04.718 --> 02:07.484
We've seen worse. Maybe once.

02:08.108 --> 02:10.054
This is getting very tiresome, Dr. Bull.

02:10.056 --> 02:11.121
Hey, hey.

02:11.123 --> 02:13.223
I totally get it. You had a monster hit,

02:13.225 --> 02:15.192
and some one-hit wonder
comes out of the woodwork

02:15.194 --> 02:17.161
and says you stole the hook to <i>his</i> song?

02:17.163 --> 02:19.029
- It's <i>your</i> song.
- That's right.

02:19.031 --> 02:20.764
And it hurts, Dr. Bull.

02:20.766 --> 02:21.832
It hurts.

02:21.834 --> 02:23.167
I know it hurts.

02:23.169 --> 02:25.335
And that's why we're gonna prove

02:25.337 --> 02:28.038
that it took you ten
years to write this song.

02:28.040 --> 02:29.073
And that it comes...

02:29.075 --> 02:30.541
(hits chest) from your soul.

02:30.543 --> 02:32.743
(quietly): I know it's about

02:32.745 --> 02:34.912
the collapse of your first marriage.

02:34.914 --> 02:36.747
And I'm sorry.

02:36.749 --> 02:39.783
But you see these people?

02:39.785 --> 02:41.048
They're the jury.

02:41.190 --> 02:43.253
They're normal, everyday folks
who come home one day,

02:43.255 --> 02:45.489
open their mail, and
they have a jury summons.

02:45.491 --> 02:47.491
They're like my fans?

02:47.493 --> 02:49.059
That's exactly what they are.

02:49.061 --> 02:50.627
They're the same people who throw

02:50.629 --> 02:52.429
panties on stage and cheer for you.

02:52.431 --> 02:54.064
And you got to see them like that.

02:54.066 --> 02:55.732
You got to talk to them like that.

02:55.734 --> 02:56.834
MARISSA: Bull?

02:56.836 --> 02:58.669
Rock on.

02:58.671 --> 03:00.304
- Go get 'em.
- MARISSA: Bull.

03:00.306 --> 03:02.406
All right. Sir Vincent
needs a fresh jury.

03:02.408 --> 03:04.159
- Thank you guys very much.
- Bull.

03:06.015 --> 03:10.080
NEWS ANCHOR: In the storm,
Essence Airlines Flight 1372

03:10.082 --> 03:13.117
went down approximately three
miles from Albany Airport.

03:13.119 --> 03:15.352
As you can see from
the wreckage behind me,

03:15.472 --> 03:19.356
all 62 passengers are presumed dead.

03:19.358 --> 03:21.458
The president of
Essence Airlines is on the line.

03:21.460 --> 03:23.660
Call back.

03:23.662 --> 03:25.762
(newscast continues)

03:25.764 --> 03:28.668
Hamilton-Sena and the
usual airline litigation firms

03:28.669 --> 03:30.000
are calling to sign us up.

03:30.002 --> 03:32.302
Crash is less than an
hour old, and the vultures

03:32.304 --> 03:34.104
- are already circling, huh?
- BULL: Missing the runway

03:34.106 --> 03:36.173
does seem to inspire lawsuits.

03:36.175 --> 03:37.674
Sorry, I'm still the new guy, but...

03:37.676 --> 03:39.276
you handled aviation suits before?

03:39.278 --> 03:40.878
Every crash in the last ten years.

03:40.880 --> 03:42.112
And, uh, Bull's a pilot.

03:42.114 --> 03:43.747
Maybe it's <i>because</i> I'm a pilot.

03:43.749 --> 03:46.049
Just spoke with a
former colleague from the FBI.

03:46.051 --> 03:47.651
- Was it...?
- Wasn't terrorism.

03:47.653 --> 03:49.853
Tried to land in a storm
with wind shear.

03:49.855 --> 03:53.023
NEWS ANCHOR: A shocking new
development, a miracle perhaps.

03:53.025 --> 03:55.225
The nose cone of the plane

03:55.227 --> 03:58.729
was severed from the
fuselage upon impact.

03:58.731 --> 04:00.998
Sources tell us that one of the pilots

04:01.000 --> 04:03.567
was pulled from the cockpit alive.

04:03.569 --> 04:06.136
Never heard of a
pilot surviving a crash.

04:06.138 --> 04:08.505
On a crash like this.

04:08.507 --> 04:12.709
Before we sign any
client... Victim or airline...

04:12.711 --> 04:14.511
We're gonna talk to this pilot.

04:14.513 --> 04:16.713
(sighs)

04:19.118 --> 04:21.185
MAN: Essence Airlines and
supporting industries

04:21.187 --> 04:24.721
have all been named in a separate
wrongful death filing.

04:24.723 --> 04:26.657
The pilot is also being sued.

04:26.659 --> 04:29.326
(reporters clamoring)

04:29.328 --> 04:33.030
There are security concerns,
because of death threats.

04:33.032 --> 04:35.432
What's the pilot's status?

04:35.434 --> 04:37.498
Thank you. That's all for today.

04:42.841 --> 04:46.009
If you needed any
convincing lawyers are overpaid,

04:46.011 --> 04:49.134
the firm owns 18 floors of
prime New York real estate.

04:49.281 --> 04:51.213
Best behavior, Dr. Bull.

04:53.307 --> 04:54.751
It's a pleasure to meet you,

04:54.753 --> 04:55.852
- Capt...
- Captain Mathison.

04:55.854 --> 04:57.621
I'm glad you fully recovered.

04:58.991 --> 05:00.224
Dr. Bull, thank you.

05:00.814 --> 05:02.926
I can't say the last four
months have been easy,

05:02.928 --> 05:04.228
but I'm here.

05:04.230 --> 05:05.229
Oscar Weber.

05:05.231 --> 05:06.496
- I'm her attorney.
- (chuckles): Oh!

05:06.498 --> 05:08.799
Gosh, yeah. I've heard so
much about you, Oscar.

05:08.801 --> 05:12.035
Thanks for taking an
interest in this case, Dr. Bull.

05:12.037 --> 05:14.805
Not sure there's a
need here for what you do.

05:14.807 --> 05:17.074
Getting the truth?

05:17.076 --> 05:17.890
Winning?

05:17.892 --> 05:19.876
We may not even take this case to trial.

05:19.878 --> 05:21.878
Captain Mathison here has been charged

05:21.880 --> 05:23.013
with gross negligence.

05:23.015 --> 05:24.681
If she were to lose in court,

05:24.683 --> 05:26.350
she may be facing criminal charges.

05:26.352 --> 05:28.151
TAYLOR: Dr. Bull, how did you know

05:28.153 --> 05:30.254
I was Captain Mathison and not him?

05:30.256 --> 05:32.122
Well, you don't bounce when you walk.

05:32.124 --> 05:33.824
So clearly you're former military,

05:33.826 --> 05:35.525
and you're wearing aviator sunglasses,

05:35.527 --> 05:37.694
so I figured... pilot.

05:37.696 --> 05:41.665
Plus, one look at Oscar, and...
there's no way <i>he's</i> a pilot.

05:41.667 --> 05:43.507
All right, let's go
hear this flight recording.

05:44.880 --> 05:46.403
TAYLOR (over computer):
Passing outer marker,

05:46.405 --> 05:47.504
ILS Approach 1-6, good to land.

05:47.506 --> 05:50.232
MAN: Radar contact, cleared to
land runway 1-6. Ceiling 2-0-0.

05:50.234 --> 05:52.535
Visibility one-quarter
mile, wind one-niner-zero,

05:52.537 --> 05:54.136
- variable 25 gust...
- Tower Albany to Flight 213...

05:54.138 --> 05:55.171
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Wind
shear. Wind shear.

05:55.173 --> 05:56.305
COPILOT: Wind shear, loss 20 knots.

05:56.307 --> 05:57.840
- TAYLOR: Cross-control 0500.
- (urgent chatter)

05:57.842 --> 05:59.441
- Can't... What are you doing?
- TAYLOR: Throttle's up!

05:59.443 --> 06:00.843
On the go... got to take it around!

06:00.845 --> 06:02.211
- Full power, full power...
- That's not protocol.

06:02.213 --> 06:03.612
TAYLOR: Clean it up, full power!

06:03.614 --> 06:05.614
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Terrain...
Pull up. Terrain... pull up.

06:05.616 --> 06:07.449
TAYLOR: Five more seconds! Brace! Brace!

06:07.451 --> 06:08.651
(sustained beep)

06:08.653 --> 06:11.020
MAN: Tower Albany, I've
lost them off-screen.

06:11.022 --> 06:12.488
You need a minute?

06:12.490 --> 06:14.790
I'm okay.

06:14.792 --> 06:17.593
Sounds like you did the best you
could in a hell of a storm.

06:17.595 --> 06:19.595
I considered flying on
to Boston early on,

06:19.597 --> 06:22.832
but the storm was worse there, so...

06:22.834 --> 06:25.100
We started our descent, and... (sighs)

06:25.102 --> 06:27.203
we hit a massive wind shear.

06:27.205 --> 06:29.638
WEBER: The challenge is
gonna be the NTSB report.

06:29.640 --> 06:32.141
It says...

06:32.143 --> 06:35.477
Captain Mathison failed to
follow emergency protocol

06:35.479 --> 06:38.247
and lost control of the plane.

06:38.249 --> 06:39.481
MARISSA: The NTSB says

06:39.483 --> 06:42.051
80% of crashes are
caused by pilot error.

06:42.053 --> 06:43.752
BULL: It's not exactly a fair fight

06:43.754 --> 06:46.655
when the pilots usually
aren't around to defend themselves.

06:46.657 --> 06:49.024
WEBER: The flight
recorder backs up the report.

06:49.026 --> 06:51.791
A jury is going to be
inclined to believe it.

06:51.945 --> 06:53.362
Unless someone bothers to give them

06:53.364 --> 06:55.464
a credible alternative explanation.

06:55.466 --> 06:57.566
Her own copilot questioned her decision.

06:57.568 --> 06:59.568
And you can read the mind of a dead man?

06:59.570 --> 07:01.036
Good for you, Oscar.

07:01.038 --> 07:03.906
Do you think you lost control?

07:03.908 --> 07:05.674
I don't remember.

07:05.676 --> 07:08.644
I wish I could tell you why
I did what I did that day,

07:08.646 --> 07:11.080
but it just...

07:11.082 --> 07:13.249
WEBER: To my point,

07:13.251 --> 07:15.651
the plaintiffs are gonna
find that very convenient.

07:15.653 --> 07:17.386
She had six broken ribs.

07:17.388 --> 07:19.021
And a severe concussion.

07:19.023 --> 07:22.157
Memory loss does
happen with head trauma.

07:23.539 --> 07:24.672
You were in the military?

07:24.674 --> 07:27.408
I flew 139 sorties over Iraq.

07:27.410 --> 07:29.476
Got over 12,000 flight hours.

07:29.478 --> 07:31.345
So what's the last
thing you do remember?

07:31.347 --> 07:33.080
The wind shear alarm.

07:33.082 --> 07:35.249
Then I woke up in the hospital.

07:36.986 --> 07:39.587
They told me everyone on the flight...

07:41.691 --> 07:45.025
And there were no survivors.

07:45.027 --> 07:46.493
And you feel responsible.

07:46.495 --> 07:49.763
My plane went down and I lost 62 souls.

07:49.765 --> 07:51.465
Of course I feel responsible.

07:51.467 --> 07:53.467
I <i>am</i> responsible.

07:53.469 --> 07:57.071
WEBER: Taylor, no one wants to see you

07:57.073 --> 08:01.175
endure a long, difficult trial.

08:01.177 --> 08:04.745
Let <i>me</i> work with the airlines.

08:04.747 --> 08:07.881
We can hash out a
settlement for these families.

08:07.883 --> 08:09.250
Lord knows

08:09.252 --> 08:11.385
what a jury is going to come back with.

08:11.387 --> 08:12.453
We'll know.

08:12.455 --> 08:14.349
Excuse me?

08:14.487 --> 08:16.490
We'll know what a
jury's gonna come back with.

08:16.492 --> 08:18.025
We'll know because that's what we do.

08:18.027 --> 08:21.595
That's what trial science is.

08:21.597 --> 08:24.632
And something to remember, Mr. Weber.

08:25.701 --> 08:28.869
Just because Taylor feels responsible

08:28.871 --> 08:30.804
doesn't mean she's to blame.

08:33.476 --> 08:36.309
Captain Mathison, I'd
like to take your case.

08:38.114 --> 08:40.514
Huh. Okay, s-so what do we do next?

08:40.515 --> 08:43.350
My team and I go to work.

08:45.955 --> 08:48.222
I didn't sleep for a week
after that plane went down.

08:48.224 --> 08:50.212
I was lead mechanic
on the gate that day.

08:50.259 --> 08:51.959
Couldn't help but
wonder if I'd missed something.

08:51.961 --> 08:53.027
How you sleeping now?

08:53.029 --> 08:54.595
Eight hours a night.

08:54.597 --> 08:56.664
Look, I did all my preflight checks.

08:56.666 --> 08:59.700
The NTSB was all up in here and
they still cleared my crew.

08:59.702 --> 09:01.969
The plane wasn't ten years old.

09:01.971 --> 09:03.804
There was barely a
grease spot on the repair log.

09:03.806 --> 09:04.805
So it was okay to fly.

09:04.807 --> 09:05.939
Waxed and ready to go.

09:05.941 --> 09:07.708
Well, that report said that the pilots

09:07.710 --> 09:09.243
did their own inspection before takeoff.

09:09.245 --> 09:11.645
- Why is that?
- They're required to do a walk-around.

09:11.647 --> 09:13.947
But it wasn't both of them
that day, it was just the copilot.

09:13.949 --> 09:15.783
Is that standard procedure?

09:15.785 --> 09:16.950
It's always the copilot.

09:16.952 --> 09:18.819
She did her walk-around
like she was supposed to.

09:18.821 --> 09:20.487
What do you... what do you mean "she"?

09:20.489 --> 09:22.256
There are lady copilots.

09:22.258 --> 09:24.658
Well, the lady wasn't the
copilot on that flight.

09:24.660 --> 09:25.793
She was the captain.

09:25.795 --> 09:27.494
I mean...

09:27.496 --> 09:28.829
Damn.

09:31.934 --> 09:33.567
JUDGE: Ladies and gentlemen of the jury,

09:33.569 --> 09:36.470
have you reached a verdict?

09:36.472 --> 09:38.205
Guilty of gross negligence.

09:38.207 --> 09:39.173
Verdict.

09:39.175 --> 09:41.416
- Guilty.
- Guilty.

09:41.669 --> 09:43.477
MARISSA: We've
questioned all of our mock jurors,

09:43.479 --> 09:45.145
and they've all found Captain
Mathison guilty.

09:45.147 --> 09:46.780
Let me work on her image.

09:46.782 --> 09:48.482
Maybe we're sending the wrong message.

09:48.484 --> 09:50.617
I have some ideas that
could balance her military edge.

09:50.619 --> 09:53.520
Worth a shot. We varied our emphasis
on her military record,

09:53.522 --> 09:55.756
her stellar pilot rating, nothing's
changed the outcome.

09:55.758 --> 09:58.025
JUDGE: Mr. Foreman, have
you reached a verdict?

09:58.027 --> 09:59.326
FOREMAN: We have, Your Honor.

09:59.328 --> 10:01.795
In the case of Berman
et al. v. Mathison,

10:01.797 --> 10:05.532
we find the defendant not guilty.

10:05.534 --> 10:07.368
Not guilty? That's amazing.

10:07.370 --> 10:08.836
How'd he do that?

10:08.838 --> 10:10.671
It is amazing.

10:10.673 --> 10:12.005
All we had to do was

10:12.007 --> 10:14.641
adjust one basic assumption
about the case.

10:14.643 --> 10:16.610
- Which one?
- Meet our client,

10:16.612 --> 10:19.546
Captain Taylor Mathison.

10:19.548 --> 10:21.515
Uh, ladies and gentlemen,

10:21.517 --> 10:24.585
all this case needed was a man's touch.

10:24.587 --> 10:25.986
(clicks tongue)

10:25.988 --> 10:28.255
Sorry. I'm just the messenger.

10:28.257 --> 10:30.195
Not the misogynist.

10:36.639 --> 10:38.348
BENNY: <i>So, juries are finding her guilty</i>

10:38.350 --> 10:40.350
- because she's a woman.
- MARISSA: But the data shows

10:40.352 --> 10:41.718
that when it comes to female pilots,

10:41.720 --> 10:43.119
there is a clear gender bias.

10:43.121 --> 10:45.221
Yeah, but it's not 1977.

10:45.223 --> 10:46.856
There are women in power everywhere.

10:46.858 --> 10:47.924
Well, it's subconscious.

10:47.926 --> 10:49.092
Things people aren't even aware of,

10:49.094 --> 10:50.593
like getting the door for a woman.

10:50.595 --> 10:52.028
BULL: Benny's always been chivalrous.

10:52.030 --> 10:53.296
CABLE: I don't get it.

10:53.298 --> 10:54.864
Is it really difficult to open a door?

10:54.866 --> 10:56.566
It's back to where
women wore farthingales.

10:56.568 --> 10:58.134
(chuckles): Farthingales.

10:58.136 --> 10:59.435
What's a farthingale?

10:59.437 --> 11:01.704
It's basically like wearing
an upside-down umbrella.

11:01.706 --> 11:03.606
All right, my point is we have to

11:03.608 --> 11:05.742
dial gender bias into Taylor's defense.

11:05.744 --> 11:08.378
- Which is?
- Which is...

11:09.648 --> 11:11.981
...an unavoidable wall of wind

11:11.983 --> 11:14.183
tragically brought down Flight 1372,

11:14.185 --> 11:17.453
and not even the skills of a
great pilot could save them.

11:17.455 --> 11:19.656
Okay. All right, I'm
gonna play devil's advocate.

11:19.658 --> 11:22.325
How do we prove she
didn't lose control of the plane

11:22.327 --> 11:23.993
if she can't even remember
what happened?

11:23.995 --> 11:25.862
Start with the flight recorder.

11:25.864 --> 11:27.363
Yeah, about that.

11:27.365 --> 11:29.899
You're aware that it only
covers the last 30 minutes

11:29.901 --> 11:31.067
before the crash?

11:31.069 --> 11:32.235
CHUNK: My phone holds

11:32.237 --> 11:34.103
1,000 hours of music, but a black box

11:34.105 --> 11:36.272
taps out halfway
through a Wayne Newton album?

11:36.274 --> 11:38.408
I tap out halfway through
a Wayne Newton album.

11:38.410 --> 11:41.377
Black box is only a piece of the puzzle.

11:41.379 --> 11:43.613
Okay, Danny, I want a play-by-play

11:43.615 --> 11:45.114
in the 24 hours of Taylor's life

11:45.116 --> 11:45.982
before the crash.

11:45.984 --> 11:47.283
And, Cable,

11:47.285 --> 11:48.985
focus on the flight itself.

11:48.987 --> 11:50.053
Fill in the blanks.

11:50.055 --> 11:51.287
Danke schoen.

11:51.289 --> 11:52.622
That's a Wayne Newton reference

11:52.624 --> 11:54.524
for your benefit, Chunk.

11:57.095 --> 11:59.395
(sighs)

12:03.234 --> 12:04.667
BULL: Cute kids.

12:04.669 --> 12:07.837
I take it you and
your copilot were close.

12:07.839 --> 12:10.173
Yeah.

12:10.175 --> 12:12.375
Ken and I were best friends.

12:12.377 --> 12:14.577
Mary and the kids are like family to me.

12:14.579 --> 12:16.612
They miss their father.

12:16.614 --> 12:18.181
It's hard for them to understand

12:18.183 --> 12:20.049
why I came home and he didn't.

12:20.051 --> 12:22.285
And Mary's mad at me.

12:22.287 --> 12:23.786
Been sitting here over an hour,

12:23.788 --> 12:25.534
and she's barely said a word.

12:26.513 --> 12:28.746
I don't know, sometimes I think she...

12:28.748 --> 12:30.848
blames me for Ken's death.

12:32.018 --> 12:33.551
Or maybe I'm just a reminder

12:33.553 --> 12:35.686
of what happened.

12:38.091 --> 12:40.258
You know, those families,
they act like I don't care

12:40.260 --> 12:42.293
about the victims, but...

12:42.295 --> 12:45.029
I think about those people every day.

12:45.031 --> 12:46.764
The void they left.

12:46.766 --> 12:49.133
The futures they don't get to have.

12:49.135 --> 12:52.437
I just keep asking myself: did I panic?

12:52.439 --> 12:55.039
You know, did I, did
I, did I take a maneuver

12:55.041 --> 12:57.075
that was too risky?

12:57.077 --> 12:59.577
Taylor, something tells me you didn't.

